"Frondel M., Oertel K., Rübbelke D.","The domino effect in climate change",2002,"International Journal of Environment and Pollution","17","3",,"202","210",,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0036275503&partnerID=40&md5=03b27511de14266cd58756bb989f392c","ZEW, Ctr. for European Economic Research, D-68161 Mannheim, Germany","Frondel, M., ZEW, Ctr. for European Economic Research, D-68161 Mannheim, Germany; Oertel, K., ZEW, Ctr. for European Economic Research, D-68161 Mannheim, Germany; Rübbelke, D., ZEW, Ctr. for European Economic Research, D-68161 Mannheim, Germany","This paper provides a concise summary of the natural and the anthropogenic greenhouse effect and the major causes for climate change. This summary may be particularly accessible for readers who are not familiar with natural sciences. Building on these explanations, we develop a simplifying atmospheric model that demonstrates a widely unknown aspect of global warming: the greenhouse effect enhances its own causes and, as a repercussion, induces a further global wanning. This effect, referred to as domino effect, is based on the additional production of heat in the atmosphere, happening substantively while heat passes our atmosphere on its way to outer space. On the basis of our considerations, in principle, technological efficiency improvements appear to be an attractive measure for mitigating global warming.","Climate change; Entropy; Global common; Technological efficiency","Earth atmosphere; Entropy; Global warming; Natural sciences; Anthropogenic greenhouse effect; Greenhouse effect",,,,,,"Bauer, A., (1993) Der Treibhauseffekt, , J.C.B. Mohr (Paul Siebeck), Tübingen; Blankart, C., (1998) Ôffentliche Finanzen in der Demokratie, , Verlag Vahlen, München; Carraro, C., Siniocalco, S., Environmental policy reconsidered: The role of technological innovation (1994) European Economic Review, 38, pp. 545-554; Cesar, H.S.J., (1994) Control and Game Models of the Greenhouse Effect: Economic Essays on the Comedy and Tragedy of Commons, , Springer, Berlin; Doornkamp, J.C., Coastal flooding, global warming and environmental management (1998) Journal of Environmental Management, 52 (4), pp. 327-333; Faber, M., Manstetten, R., Proops, J., Baumgärtner, S., Entropy: A unifying concept for ecological economies (1996) Ecological Economics: Concepts and Methods, pp. 95-114. , Edward Elgar, Cheltenham, Brookfield; Falk, G., Ruppel, W., (1976) Energie und Entropie - Eine Einführung in die Thermodynamik, , Springer Verlag, Berlin; Faucheux, S., Pillet, G., Energy metrics: On various valuation properties of energy (1994) Valuing the Environment: Methodological and Measurement Issues, pp. 273-309. , Pethig, R. (Editor) Kluwer Academic Publishers, Dordrecht; Frondel, M., (1997) Thermodynamik und der ökonomische Prozeß, , Discussion Paper No. 243, University of Heidelberg; Hardin, G., The tragedy of commons (1968) Science, 162, pp. 1243-1248; Gilli, P.V., Nakicenovic, N., Kurz, R., First- and second-law efficiencies of the global and regional energy systems (1995) Proceedings of the 16th WEC Congress, , Research Report, More Efficient Use of Energy, Division 3 of Energy for Our Common World, World Energy Council, 8-13 October 1995, Tokyo; Gorshkov, V.G., Oceanic dissolved organic carbon is the main sink of atmospheric CO2 (1997) World Resource Review, 9 (2), pp. 153-169; (1997) Climate Change: The IPCC Scientific Assessment, , IPCC, Cambridge University Press, Cambridge, UK; Khanna, M., Zilberman, D., Incentives, precision technology and environmental protection (1997) Ecological Economics, 23 (1), pp. 25-43; Murota, T., Environmental economics of the water planet Earth (1987) Environmental Economics. The Analysis of a Major Interface, pp. 185-199. , Pillet, G. and Murota, T. (Editors) Roland Leimgruber, Geneva; Nordhaus, W.D., (1994) Managing the Global Commons, , The MIT Press, Cambridge; Ostrom, E., Gardner, R., Walker, J., (1997) Rules, Games and Common-Pool Resources,